lic \u03b1-ketoacid networks linked to glycine synthesis. This reaction anchors cross-environment connectivity rather than serving as the sole glycine route (Roldan et al., 2015; Muchowska et al., 2019; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface UV photochemistry producing hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"strong UV irradiation; evaporitic or subaerial photochemical setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven dehydration and redox fragmentation of simple C-N-O feedstocks yields cyanide available for Strecker and cyanosulfidic chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The knowledge base supports UV photochemistry linking HCN and formamide-type chemistry in prebiotic environments, although mineral-specific evidence for glycine-focused UV catalysis is limited. TiO2 is included to satisfy the required mineral specification for surface photochemistry and as a plausible photocatalytic mineral; this step is therefore partially literature-supported and explicitly somewhat speculative in mineral assignment while remaining consistent with the supplied framework (Saladino et al., 2012; Patel et al., 2015; reviewed in sources 10826, 21196).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface UV hydration of HCN to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV exposure in shallow pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical hydration/rearrangement of cyanide in aqueous surface settings gives formamide as a reservoir C-N intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a recognized UV-accessible intermediate in prebiotic chemistry from HCN and water. Although this branch is not the dominant glycine route, it creates a literature-grounded reversible C-N pool and supports environmental interconnection. Clay is included as a concentrating/stabilizing surface mineral consistent with the supplied instructions (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015; reviewed in source 10826).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Formation of aminomethanol from formaldehyde and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous, near-neutral to alkaline conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia adds to formaldehyde to form the carbinolamine aminomethanol, a documented Strecker intermediate preceding imine/aminonitrile formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminomethanol has been experimentally identified as a key intermediate in Strecker synthesis relevant to glycine. Including it explicitly corrects prior underspecification and follows the research findings directly. Surface minerals are assigned as concentrating agents rather than proven essential catalysts for this exact elementary step (Danger et al., 2012; Bossa et al., 2009; reviewed in source 10878).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation: formaldehyde to glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-accessible, mildly alkaline surface pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN adds to formaldehyde to generate the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile, a central precursor in Strecker and cyanosulfidic networks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature report explicitly identifies cyanohydrins and glyconitrile/glycolonitrile as key intermediates in glycine formation and cyanosulfidic protometabolism. This is one of the strongest supported surface steps in the network (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2016; reviewed in sources 9376, 10835, 21196).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Amination of glycolonitrile to aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous alkaline to near-neutral conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonolysis/substitution at the cyanohydrin-derived intermediate converts glycolonitrile into the \u03b1-aminonitrile aminoacetonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitriles are the immediate Strecker precursors to amino acids and are explicitly highlighted in the research findings for glycine synthesis. This step captures the literature-supported progression from cyanohydrin-type intermediates to aminonitriles in aqueous prebiotic settings (Elsila et al., 2007; Danger et al., 2013; reviewed in sources 10835, 21189, 9381).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker capture of aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"near-neutral pH; phosphoro-Strecker-like regime with phosphate activation represented by mineral phosphate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde, cyanide, and ammonia react in a phosphate-rich aqueous setting to trap Strecker intermediates and furnish aminoacetonitrile efficiently under mild conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature findings specifically note near-neutral phosphoro-Strecker variants in water that form N-phosphoroaminonitriles and channel amino-acid precursor formation while suppressing side products. Diamidophosphate itself is not represented as a separate molecule to keep the graph compact, so phosphate minerals are used as the environmental phosphate source; this is a simplified but literature-guided encoding of the phosphoro-Strecker branch (Gibard et al., 2018; Danger et al., 2020; reviewed in sources 21189, 21190, 21192).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pool hydrolysis; repeated heating/cooling can assist despite known kinetic barrier\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential nitrile hydration and hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile to the amino acid glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the canonical terminal step of Strecker synthesis. The report explicitly notes aminoacetonitrile as immediate precursor and hydrolysis as a challenge because of high energy barriers, so the step is included as rate-limiting and environmentally dependent rather than assumed effortless (Miller, 1957; Peltzer et al., 1984; reviewed in sources 10797, 10835, 15642, 16363).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of glycolonitrile to glycolic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous alteration in pools or parent-body-like settings\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis converts glycolonitrile into the \u03b1-hydroxy acid glycolic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The knowledge base explicitly links formaldehyde and HCN to glycolic acid through cyanide-derived intermediates and notes glycolic acid as a variant Strecker-associated precursor in glycine-forming systems. This reaction also reflects aqueous alteration chemistry relevant to meteoritic contexts (Lerner et al., 1993; Pizzarello & Holmes, 2009; reviewed in source 2618).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxidation of glycolic acid to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"borate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed evaporitic pool; oxidative photochemistry without molecular oxygen\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical or mineral-assisted oxidation of the \u03b1-hydroxy acid produces the \u03b1-keto acid glyoxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report emphasizes glyoxylate as a central intermediate in cyanosulfidic protometabolism and notes progression from glycolate-type intermediates toward carboxylate chemistry enabling metabolic switching. Exact geochemical oxidation chemistry remains incompletely resolved, so this step is moderately speculative but directly motivated by the literature's central role for glyoxylate (Patel et al., 2015; Muchowska et al., 2020; reviewed in sources 9797, 23036, 6944).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of glyoxylate to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH about 8; reductive amination/transamination-like prebiotic pool conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyoxylate undergoes imine formation with ammonia followed by reduction to furnish glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research findings explicitly cite glyoxylate as a central precursor to glycine and mention glycine formation through reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoacids facilitated by reductants such as metallic iron in prebiotic contexts. Because the Biochemical stage allows variable prebiotic assembly conditions, this reaction is encoded without mineral requirement while keeping the literature-supported chemistry (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003; Muchowska et al., 2019; reviewed in sources 9396, 23036).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-centered protometabolic conversion to glyoxylate-equivalent oxidation state\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"inert atmosphere; aldol/retro-aldol and redox-active protometabolic network conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate participates in non-enzymatic protometabolic redox and carbon-skeleton rearrangements that access glyoxylate-linked products and other ketoacids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary states that glyoxylate and pyruvate undergo aldol/retro-aldol, hydration/dehydration, oxidative decarboxylation, and redox processes under prebiotic conditions around 70\u00b0C, generating TCA-like intermediates and feeding amino-acid chemistry. Mesoxalate is included as a connected oxidation product to preserve network topology, but the key supported outcome is access to glyoxylate-centered chemistry from pyruvate (Muchowska et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020; reviewed in sources 9400, 6944, 995).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Strecker via glycolonitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced C1 carbon feeds a surface Strecker sequence through glycolonitrile and aminoacetonitrile, followed by aminonitrile hydrolysis to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Aminomethanol-assisted Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde first captures ammonia as aminomethanol before converging back to the glycolonitrile/aminoacetonitrile branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Near-neutral phosphate-rich surface chemistry forms aminoacetonitrile directly from formaldehyde, HCN, and ammonia, then hydrolyzes to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-formamide-cyanide recycle Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"A UV-cycled HCN/formamide surface pool feeds back into Strecker chemistry, ending in aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolonitrile hydrolysis to glycolate then oxidation to glyoxylate\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanohydrin chemistry branches through glycolic acid and glyoxylate before final reductive amination to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal glycolate branch to glyoxylate\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde-derived glycolic acid is exported to the surface, oxidized to glyoxylate, then aminated to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic glycolonitrile-glyoxylate convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycolonitrile serves both as Strecker intermediate and as precursor to glycolate/glyoxylate in a cyanosulfidic-style branch culminating in glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-to-glyoxylate protometabolic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate enters a surface protometabolic redox network that accesses glyoxylate, followed by glyoxylate amination to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Mixed hydrothermal-surface convergence on glyoxylate\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal glycolate production and hydrothermal pyruvate production converge through separate surface transformations on glyoxylate, which is then converted to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual-convergence network route via aminoacetonitrile and glyoxylate\",\n      \"description\": \"Aminoacetonitrile and glyoxylate routes coexist in the same connected network, giving alternative terminal conversions to glycine from shared surface feedstocks.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Glycine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets glycine through literature-grounded convergence on four major hub intermediates: formaldehyde, hydrogen cyanide, glycolonitrile, and aminoacetonitrile, with glyoxylate as a secondary metabolic hub. The design emphasizes (i) hydrothermal generation of reduced C1 feedstocks and \u03b1-keto/carboxylate intermediates on iron-sulfur minerals, (ii) surface Strecker and cyanosulfidic chemistry under aqueous, UV-exposed, wet-dry conditions with required mineral agents, and (iii) biochemical/prebiotic hydrolysis, transamination, and compartment-linked concentration steps that deliver glycine. Ten distinct pathways are encoded as different valid reaction sequences through the same connected bipartite graph. The network avoids unsupported direct glycolic-acid-to-glycine conversion and instead routes through literature-supported aminonitrile hydrolysis or glyoxylate amination/transamination.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "aminomethanol", "common_name": "aminomethanol", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH5NO/c2-1-3/h3H,1-2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetonitrile", "common_name": "aminoacetonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h2H,4H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetic acid", "common_name": "glycolic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h3H,1H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "CHNO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H4O4", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanedioic acid", "common_name": "mesoxalic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H2O5/c4-1(2(5)6)3(7)8/h(H,5,6)(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde-equivalent C1 feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "elemental iron"], "conditions": {"temperature": "448-523K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and elemental iron", "aqueous": "true", "other": "serpentinization-like reducing conditions; formaldehyde represented as reduced C1 product accessible from hydrothermal carbon fixation"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 on Fe-bearing surfaces yields reduced one-carbon products; formaldehyde is represented as the reactive carbonyl feedstock entering downstream prebiotic chemistry.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal systems generate reduced C1 carbon through Fe-bearing mineral catalysis and serpentinization chemistry, providing plausible formaldehyde-equivalent feedstocks for glycine-forming networks. The specific importance of formaldehyde as primary carbon source for hydrothermal glycine-forming chemistry is supported by hydrothermal amino-acid experiments and carbon-tracing studies, although free formaldehyde accumulation is less directly established than formate or methanol; this step is therefore a necessary but partially inferential connector grounded in hydrothermal carbon-fixation literature and glycine-forming hydrothermal systems (Cody et al., 2000; Keller et al., 2014; McCollom, 2013; reviewed in the provided report citing sources 13497, 13483, 13485, 23030, 23045)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of glycolic acid from formaldehyde-derived carbon", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite", "mackinawite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "448-523K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subcritical to hydrothermal water; organo-mineral interaction regime"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde-derived hydrothermal carbon is converted through oxidation/rearrangement chemistry to glycolic acid, a reported intermediate in glycine-producing hydrothermal systems.", "reasoning": "The literature summary explicitly identifies glycolic acid as a key intermediate in hydrothermal and Strecker-related glycine formation from formaldehyde-derived carbon, and carbon-tracing work supports its role in the route to glycine. This reaction is retained because glycolic acid is specifically named in the research findings, but exact single-step stoichiometry in hydrothermal media remains simplified here; the step is therefore moderately supported rather than fully resolved mechanistically (Marshall, 1994; Islam et al., 2003; reviewed in sources 2608, 11370, 13497)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite", "magnetite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent-like reducing setting"}, "mechanism": "Iron-sulfur and iron-oxide mineral surfaces mediate progressive CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation to \u03b1-keto acid products, represented here by pyruvate.", "reasoning": "The user-provided hydrothermal framework explicitly lists pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2 on magnetite/greigite as a key vent reaction type. Pyruvate is also relevant to cyanosulfidic protometabolism and protometabolic \u03b1-ketoacid networks linked to glycine synthesis. This reaction anchors cross-environment connectivity rather than serving as the sole glycine route (Roldan et al., 2015; Muchowska et al., 2019; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface UV photochemistry producing hydrogen cyanide", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "strong UV irradiation; evaporitic or subaerial photochemical setting"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven dehydration and redox fragmentation of simple C-N-O feedstocks yields cyanide available for Strecker and cyanosulfidic chemistry.", "reasoning": "The knowledge base supports UV photochemistry linking HCN and formamide-type chemistry in prebiotic environments, although mineral-specific evidence for glycine-focused UV catalysis is limited. TiO2 is included to satisfy the required mineral specification for surface photochemistry and as a plausible photocatalytic mineral; this step is therefore partially literature-supported and explicitly somewhat speculative in mineral assignment while remaining consistent with the supplied framework (Saladino et al., 2012; Patel et al., 2015; reviewed in sources 10826, 21196)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface UV hydration of HCN to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV exposure in shallow pools"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical hydration/rearrangement of cyanide in aqueous surface settings gives formamide as a reservoir C-N intermediate.", "reasoning": "Formamide is a recognized UV-accessible intermediate in prebiotic chemistry from HCN and water. Although this branch is not the dominant glycine route, it creates a literature-grounded reversible C-N pool and supports environmental interconnection. Clay is included as a concentrating/stabilizing surface mineral consistent with the supplied instructions (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015; reviewed in source 10826)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Formation of aminomethanol from formaldehyde and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous, near-neutral to alkaline conditions"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia adds to formaldehyde to form the carbinolamine aminomethanol, a documented Strecker intermediate preceding imine/aminonitrile formation.", "reasoning": "Aminomethanol has been experimentally identified as a key intermediate in Strecker synthesis relevant to glycine. Including it explicitly corrects prior underspecification and follows the research findings directly. Surface minerals are assigned as concentrating agents rather than proven essential catalysts for this exact elementary step (Danger et al., 2012; Bossa et al., 2009; reviewed in source 10878)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation: formaldehyde to glycolonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide mi