cite glyoxylate as a central precursor to glycine and mention glycine formation through reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoacids facilitated by reductants such as metallic iron in prebiotic contexts. Because the Biochemical stage allows variable prebiotic assembly conditions, this reaction is encoded without mineral requirement while keeping the literature-supported chemistry (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003; Muchowska et al., 2019; reviewed in sources 9396, 23036)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Pyruvate-centered protometabolic conversion to glyoxylate-equivalent oxidation state", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals and TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "inert atmosphere; aldol/retro-aldol and redox-active protometabolic network conditions"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate participates in non-enzymatic protometabolic redox and carbon-skeleton rearrangements that access glyoxylate-linked products and other ketoacids.", "reasoning": "The literature summary states that glyoxylate and pyruvate undergo aldol/retro-aldol, hydration/dehydration, oxidative decarboxylation, and redox processes under prebiotic conditions around 70\u00b0C, generating TCA-like intermediates and feeding amino-acid chemistry. Mesoxalate is included as a connected oxidation product to preserve network topology, but the key supported outcome is access to glyoxylate-centered chemistry from pyruvate (Muchowska et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020; reviewed in sources 9400, 6944, 995)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical Strecker via glycolonitrile", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced C1 carbon feeds a surface Strecker sequence through glycolonitrile and aminoacetonitrile, followed by aminonitrile hydrolysis to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010"], "key_in