\": \"pH about 8; prebiotic pool or mineral interface; compatible with reported glyoxylate-centered protometabolism\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyoxylate undergoes amination/reductive amination or transamination to produce glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The provided findings identify glyoxylate as a central precursor and mention glycine formation through transamination of glyoxylate under pH 8 and about 50 C conditions, as well as reductive amination concepts in protometabolic chemistry. This step is therefore literature-supported and chemically stronger than the rejected direct glycolic-acid amination used previously (Muchowska et al., 2019; source 23061; source 9396 summarized in the report).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanohydrin Strecker pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced carbon feeds surface HCN chemistry; formaldehyde forms glycolonitrile, which is aminated to aminoacetonitrile and hydrolyzed to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Aminomethanol-mediated Strecker pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde first reacts with ammonia to form aminomethanol, then HCN trapping gives aminoacetonitrile followed by hydrolysis to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker near-neutral pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Aminoacetonitrile formed by Strecker chemistry is captured under phosphate-rich conditions as a phosphoroaminonitrile and then hydrolyzed to glycine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_00