aldehyde in hydrothermal glycine-forming systems and emphasizes hydrothermal formose/formaldehyde-ammonia chemistry. This step is therefore represented as a network-level formaldehyde-to-glycolic acid conversion within experimentally observed hydrothermal reaction mixtures rather than a single isolated textbook oxidation (Imai et al., 1999; Kebukawa et al., 2013; Parker et al., 2014 as reflected in the provided hydrothermal evidence summary)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface HCN generation and concentration in UV-exposed evaporitic settings", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed shallow pools; photoredox generation/concentration of cyanide family species under anoxic conditions"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven surface photochemistry in mineral-rich pools produces and concentrates reactive cyanide feedstocks needed for Strecker and cyanosulfidic pathways.", "reasoning": "The glycine literature requires HCN as a core feedstock for Strecker and cyanosulfidic routes. While exact mineral catalysis for glycine-specific UV HCN generation is not given in the provided database, UV-mineral surface chemistry is necessary to connect the documented HCN-dependent routes; this reaction is therefore a conservative connecting step using required surface mineral agents and should be regarded as partially speculative but consistent with prebiotic cyanide photochemistry (Sutherland, 2016; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Aminomethanol formation from formaldehyde and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous conditions; near-neutral to mildly alkaline pH"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia addition to formaldehyde gives aminomethanol as a reversible imine-hydration equivalent in Strecker pre-equilibrium chemistry.", "reasoning": "Aminomethanol is explicitly identified in the supplied literature findings as an experimentally observed key intermediate in glycine Strecker synthesis. Its inclusion resolves a deficiency noted in prior attempts and makes the Strecker branch mechanistically explicit (Bossa et al., 2009/2010-type Strecker mechanistic studies as summarized in source 10878; general Strecker context from Peltzer et al. and related studies in the provided report)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Glycolonitrile formation by cyanohydrin chemistry from formaldehyde and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals and TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed cyanosulfidic setting; neutral to mildly alkaline pH"}, "mechanism": "HCN adds to formaldehyde to form the \u03b1-hydroxynitrile glycolonitrile, a cyanohydrin hub shared by Strecker and cyanosulfidic chemistry.", "reasoning": "The supplied report directly identifies glyconitrile/glycolonitrile as a central cyanosulfidic intermediate derived from formaldehyde and HCN and relevant to glycine formation. This is a well-supported convergence point in the network (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; source 9376 in the provided findings)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Aminoacetonitrile formation from glycolonitrile and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous alkaline or near-neutral conditions; aminonitrile-forming Strecker regime"}, "mechanism": "Ammonolysis/imine-equilibration of the cyanohydrin gives the \u03b1-aminonitrile aminoacetonitrile.", "reasoning": "Aminonitriles are explicitly listed in the provided research as the key Strecker intermediates en route to glycine. This step is the canonical bridge from cyanohydrin chemistry to amino acid formation (Elsila et al., 2007; Peltzer et al., 1984; source set 6942, 11365, 6985, 21189 summarized in the report)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Direct Strecker-type aminoacetonitrile formation from aminomethanol and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite and TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous conditions; neutral to mildly alkaline pH"}, "mechanism": "HCN traps the aminomethanol/iminium-equivalent intermediate to yield aminoacetonitrile.", "reasoning": "The supplied knowledge base specifically highlights aminomethanol as a key Strecker intermediate; this reaction makes that branch explicit and distinct from the glycolonitrile-first route. It addresses the previous failure where aminomethanol was not connected to aminoacetonitrile formation as a distinct graph edge (Bossa et al., 2009/2010-type mechanistic evidence summarized in source 10878; Strecker framework from the sources summarized under 10835 and 21189)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Phosphoro-Strecker capture of aminoacetonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate minera